[suggestions]
  LENS     adversarial-input
           A semver parser is a string parser — it's a target for malformed input, ReDoS via backtracking regexes, and extremely long version strings. An adversarial lens would surface robustness requirements.
  QUESTION Should the library support loose/coercion mode or strict-only?
           This is the single biggest design decision that affects every parsing function. node-semver supports both modes, but loose mode adds significant complexity. The POD/simplicity philosophy suggests strict-only, but real-world package metadata is messy.
  QUESTION What is the performance budget — how many satisfies() calls per second are needed?
           A lockfile resolver may call satisfies() millions of times during dependency resolution. This determines whether to pre-compile ranges into a fast evaluator or keep the simple parse-every-time approach.
  SOURCE   https://github.com/npm/node-semver/blob/main/test/fixtures/range-include.js
           node-semver's own test fixtures are the canonical truth table for range behavior — invaluable for building a compatible implementation.
  SOURCE   https://semver.org/spec/v2.0.0.html
           The authoritative spec. Section 11 (precedence) and the BNF grammar are essential references for the parser.
  LENS     api-ergonomics
           The worldview focuses on what the library does but not how it feels to use. A lens on API design would explore: chainable vs. functional, error reporting style, whether Range is opaque or inspectable, and how to handle the common case (satisfies) vs. advanced cases (intersection, sorting).

